---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { site } from '../../content';

const path = '/compare/klaviyo-vs-mailchimp';
const title = 'Klaviyo vs Mailchimp for Shopify Email Tools: 2026 Comparison';
const desc = 'Klaviyo vs Mailchimp for Shopify email tools — lifecycle automation vs familiar campaigns, ecommerce triggers vs general marketing breadth, and when to leave the editor you already know.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Is Mailchimp still viable for Shopify stores in 2026?',
    answer: 'Yes for broadcast-heavy shops under ~350 orders/month that primarily need newsletters, sale announcements, and a simple welcome drip. Mailchimp becomes a revenue leak when cart recovery, browse follow-up, replenishment timing, and sale-week suppression require ecommerce-native logic — jobs Klaviyo handles without weekly CSV exports.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What breaks first when scaling Mailchimp on Shopify?',
    answer: 'Cross-flow suppression. A climbing-gear shop on Mailchimp Customer Journeys could not easily exclude shoppers in active welcome series from cart recovery without manual list splits. Browse-triggered emails are weak. Product blocks lag on multi-variant carts. Reporting attributes clicks, not incremental lifecycle revenue by journey.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How do Klaviyo and Mailchimp compare at 12,000 contacts?',
    answer: 'Mailchimp Standard often runs $150–220/mo; Klaviyo lands $180–300/mo depending on SMS. Similar sticker prices, different output — Klaviyo typically recovers more cart and browse revenue when flows are live. Both bill on contacts/profiles; neither fixes list hygiene automatically. Sunset unengaged before comparing invoices.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can Mailchimp handle replenishment for consumables?',
    answer: 'Awkwardly. A specialty tea merchant can time reorder reminders with tags and purchase date fields, but per-SKU consumption windows and subscription suppression take workarounds. Klaviyo supports SKU-level replenishment with predicted reorder for bundle buyers. If repeat purchase timing is core revenue, Mailchimp is a temporary host.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the safest Klaviyo migration path from Mailchimp?',
    answer: 'Week one: export consent timestamps, rebuild welcome and cart in Klaviyo, pause Mailchimp automations before enabling equivalents. Week two: parallel suppression monitoring. Week three: post-purchase and winback. Week four: deliverability and sunset audit. Do not migrate the week before a product drop.',
  },
  {
    question: 'When does Mailchimp win despite Klaviyo hype?',
    answer: 'When your team lives in Mailchimp for non-ecommerce features — landing pages, surveys, lightweight CRM pipelines — and Shopify revenue is still a minority of the business. Also when switching cost genuinely exceeds 12 months of incremental lifecycle GMV. Familiarity is a real asset; it is not a retention strategy.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I consider Sequenzy instead of both?',
    answer: 'Sequenzy fits when Mailchimp is too shallow and Klaviyo feels heavy or expensive — agent-first lifecycle playbooks with send-based pricing. Klaviyo still wins on predictive maximums. Mailchimp still wins on generalist marketing breadth outside Shopify retention.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What workflow test decides the winner?',
    answer: 'Build four flows in both: welcome branched by signup source, abandoned checkout with dynamic variants, post-purchase excluding gift orders, winback split by engagement. If Mailchimp needs exports or duplicate journeys for two of four, schedule migration. Score edit safety during a sale week, not demo templates.',
  },
];
